becoming teen mothers, or being involved with boyfriends in gangs.Latina Girls brings together cutting edge research that challenges these stereotypes. At the same time, the volume offers solid data and suggestions for practical intervention for those who study and work to support this population. It highlights the challenges these young women face, as well as the ways in which they successfully negotiate those challenges. The volume includes research on Latinas and their relationships with family, friends, and romantic partners; academics; career goals; identity; lifelong satisfaction; and the ways in which they navigate across cultures and gender roles.Latina Girls is the first book to pull together research on the overall strengths and strategies that characterize Latina adolescents' lives in the U.S. It will be of key interest and practical use to those who study and work with Latina youth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHispanic American teenage girlsxPsychology. 0aHispanic American teenage girlsxSocial conditions. 0aHispanic AmericansxEthnic identity. 0aSex rolezUnited States. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Developmental / Adolescent.2bisacsh  aLatinas.  aacademics.  aacross.  acareer.  acultures.  afamily.  afriends.  agender.  agoals.  aidentity.  aincludes.  alifelong.  anavigate.  apartners.  arelationships.  aresearch.  aroles.  aromantic.  asatisfaction.  atheir.  athey.  avolume.  aways.  awhich.  awith.1 aArruda, Elise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAyala, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBangi, Audrey K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenner, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenner, Jill, eeditor